Phenylethanoid glycosides represent the largest group of natural products identified in parasitic plants of the family Orobanchaceae . Due to the fact that PhG compounds are usually not found in host species, they are considered as specialized metabolites synthesized by the parasites, as opposed to compounds sequestered from the hosts (alkaloids, flavonoids, and polyacetylenes) (
). Nevertheless, the occurrence of phenylethanoid glycosides has also been reported in many other non-parasitic plants, especially from the order Lamiales , including the families Oleaceae , Plantaginaceae , and
Scrophulariaceae ( Jiménez and Riguera, 1994 )
. The physiological role of specialized metabolites in broomrapes, such as PhGs, is not fully understood (the lack of literature data in this topic). Due to the demonstrated antibacterial and antimicrobial activity of phenylethanoid glycosides, it has been proposed that their role in the plants may be associated with the resistance to, or protection from, pathogenic microorganisms attacks (
).

